This is the "Golden Path" to your minimal Linux system. 
We will compile the Kernel, build a static BusyBox (with your tc fix), 
and structure a proper root filesystem into the ~/boot directory.

1. Environment Setup
Install the required tools for building the kernel and packing the filesystem.

sudo apt update && sudo apt install -y build-essential libncurses-dev bison flex libssl-dev libelf-dev qemu-system-x86 wget xorriso syslinux isolinux 
cd ~
mkdir -p ~/boot ~/rootfs

2. Compile the Linux Kernel
We use the standard x86 configuration which includes the drivers needed for QEMU.

cd ~
# Note : kernel.org is the official source 
# Latest Kernel
#git clone --depth 1 https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/stable/linux.git
#git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/torvalds/linux.git
# Stable as for now 
git clone --depth 1 --branch v6.19.10 https://git.kernel.org/pub/scm/linux/kernel/git/stable/linux.git
#git clone --depth 1 --branch v6.19 https://github.com/torvalds/linux.git
cd linux

# Generate the default 64-bit configuration
make x86_64_defconfig
#make menuconfig

# Compile the kernel (this takes a few minutes)
make -j$(nproc)

# Move the resulting binary to your boot folder
mkdir ~/boot
cp arch/x86/boot/bzImage ~/boot/vmlinuz

3. Compile BusyBox (with tc Fix)
We use the official mirror and apply your sed commands to bypass the networking header errors.

cd ~
wget https://busybox.net/downloads/busybox-1.36.1.tar.bz2
tar xjf busybox-1.36.1.tar.bz2
cd busybox-1.36.1

# Create the initial config
make defconfig

# Fix the 'tc' compilation error and ensure the build is static
sed -i 's/CONFIG_TC=y/# CONFIG_TC is not set/' .config
sed -i 's/CONFIG_FEATURE_TC_INGRESS=y/# CONFIG_FEATURE_TC_INGRESS is not set/' .config
sed -i 's/# CONFIG_STATIC is not set/CONFIG_STATIC=y/' .config

# Build and install to the local _install directory
make -j$(nproc)
make install

4. Build the Root Filesystem (Rootfs)
The Kernel needs a specific structure to find the "Init" process.

# Clean the staging area and copy BusyBox files
cd ~
mkdir ~/rootfs
rm -rf ~/rootfs/*
cd ~/rootfs
cp -av ~/busybox-*/_install/* .

# Create essential system directories
mkdir -p dev proc sys etc/init.d tmp root

# Create the startup script that mounts systems and handles devices
cat << 'EOF' > etc/init.d/rcS
#!/bin/sh
mount -t proc proc /proc
mount -t sysfs sysfs /sys
mount -t devtmpfs devtmpfs /dev
mdev -s
echo "----------------------------------------"
echo "       Minimal_Linux_System-MLS         "
echo "----------------------------------------"
EOF

chmod +x etc/init.d/rcS

# Create the primary init file (the first thing the kernel runs)
cat << 'EOF' > init
#!/bin/sh
# Handoff control to the BusyBox init system
exec /sbin/init
EOF

chmod +x init

5. Pack and Boot
Now we create the initrd.img (Initial RAM Disk) and launch QEMU.

# Pack the filesystem
cd ~
cd ~/rootfs
find . -print0 | cpio --null -ov --format=newc | gzip -9 > ~/boot/initrd.img

6. Boot the created Linux image and initramfs in QEMU
# Boot the system
cd ~
qemu-system-x86_64 \
    -kernel ~/boot/vmlinuz \
    -initrd ~/boot/initrd.img \
    -nographic \
    -append "console=ttyS0"

###############################################################################
# Create an bootable iso from it 
1. Prepare the ISO Workspace
We'll create a clean directory to house the ISO contents and copy your files into it.

# Create the structure
mkdir -p ~/iso_build/boot/isolinux

# Copy your kernel and initrd
cp ~/boot/vmlinuz ~/iso_build/boot/
cp ~/boot/initrd.img ~/iso_build/boot/

# Copy the bootloader files (standard locations on Debian/Ubuntu)
cp /usr/lib/ISOLINUX/isolinux.bin ~/iso_build/boot/isolinux/
cp /usr/lib/syslinux/modules/bios/ldlinux.c32 ~/iso_build/boot/isolinux/

2. Create the Configuration File
This file tells the BIOS how to handle the vmlinuz and initrd.img files you just moved.

cat <<EOF > ~/iso_build/boot/isolinux/isolinux.cfg
default linux
label linux
  kernel /boot/vmlinuz
  append initrd=/boot/initrd.img console=tty0
EOF

3. Generate the ISO
We use xorriso to wrap these files into a bootable image format.

xorriso -as mkisofs -o ~/linux_bootable.iso \
  -b boot/isolinux/isolinux.bin -c boot/isolinux/boot.cat \
  -no-emul-boot -boot-load-size 4 -boot-info-table \
  ~/iso_build
  
4. Verify and Test
You can quickly check if the ISO actually boots using qemu. 
This saves you from burning a USB drive only to find a configuration error.  

# Run the ISO in a virtual machine
qemu-system-x86_64 -cdrom ~/linux_bootable.iso -m 1G
